You are a security researcher at a fraud immunity lab generating synthetic money-laundering scenarios. These scenarios are used exclusively to train and evaluate fraud ring detection systems — never for actual crimes.

Generate a single, detailed money-laundering scenario as a JSON object. The scenario must model a realistic laundering chain that a sophisticated actor would use to evade detection.

## Attack Parameters
- Attack type: money_laundering
- Complexity: {{ complexity }}
- Target segment: {{ target_segment }}
- Required evasion tactics: {{ evasion_tactics | join(", ") }}

## Output Schema (strict — return ONLY this JSON, no explanation)
{
  "attack_type": "money_laundering",
  "complexity": "{{ complexity }}",
  "target_segment": "{{ target_segment }}",
  "evasion_tactics": ["<tactic_1>", "<tactic_2>", ...],
  "transaction_pattern": {
    "placement_method": "<cash_deposit|structuring|trade_based|crypto>",
    "layering_hops": <integer 2-6>,
    "total_amount_range_usd": [<min_integer>, <max_integer>],
    "structuring": {
      "enabled": <true|false>,
      "below_ctr_threshold_usd": <integer, typically 9000 or 8500>,
      "frequency_per_week": <integer>
    },
    "account_chain": [
      {
        "hop": 1,
        "role": "placement",
        "account_type": "<personal|business|shell>",
        "jurisdiction": "<domestic|offshore|high_risk_country>",
        "transaction_type": "<deposit|transfer|wire>"
      }
    ],
    "round_trip": <true|false>,
    "time_span_days": <integer 1-90>
  },
  "expected_detection_signals": [
    "<community_detection_fraud_ring|structuring_pattern|velocity_anomaly|cross_border_flow|unidirectional_flow|...>"
  ]
}

## Constraints
- account_chain must have entries matching layering_hops count.
- Do NOT include real financial institution names, real account numbers, or real individual names.
- Use placeholder values only (e.g., "account_hop_1", "shell_co_abc").
- If structuring.enabled is true, below_ctr_threshold_usd must be less than 10000.
- expected_detection_signals must name at least 3 specific signals detectable by graph analysis.
- Return only the JSON object — no markdown, no explanation.
